<header class="header">
  <h1>Insect Netting vs Row Cover for Brassicas</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    The best choice depends on whether you need more pest protection or more temperature protection.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most brassica crops, insect netting is better for pest control in warmer conditions, while row cover is better for early-season protection when cold is also a factor.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Brassicas like cabbage, broccoli, kale, and cauliflower benefit from physical protection, but the type of cover you use changes how the plants grow and what problems you prevent.
  </p>
  <p>
    Insect netting and row cover look similar, but they serve slightly different purposes. Choosing the right one depends on your timing, your climate, and what you are trying to protect against.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: Which Should You Use?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Use insect netting:</strong> when pest pressure is the main problem.</li>
      <li><strong>Use row cover:</strong> when both cold and pests are concerns.</li>
      <li><strong>Use both (at different times):</strong> in many gardens, this gives the best results.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    Many gardeners start with row cover early in the season and switch to insect netting as temperatures rise.
  </p>
</section>

