<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Insect Netting Is the Better Choice</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Pest pressure is high:</strong> especially cabbage worms or flea beetles.</li>
    <li><strong>Temperatures are warm:</strong> airflow becomes more important.</li>
    <li><strong>You want minimal impact on plant growth conditions.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Insect netting focuses on keeping pests out without significantly changing the environment around the plant.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-insect-netting-for-brassicas/">best insect netting for brassicas</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Row Cover Is the Better Choice</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Cold protection is needed:</strong> especially early in the season.</li>
    <li><strong>You want to buffer temperature swings.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Pests are present but not the only concern.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Row cover adds a layer of temperature protection while still helping reduce pest access.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-row-cover-for-early-spring-brassicas/">best row cover for early spring brassicas</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Many Gardeners Use Both</h2>

  <p>
    In many climates, the best approach is not choosing one or the other, but using each at the right time.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Early season:</strong> row cover protects from cold and early pests.</li>
    <li><strong>Mid season:</strong> switch to insect netting for better airflow.</li>
    <li><strong>Late season:</strong> use netting to maintain pest protection without overheating.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This approach matches the changing needs of brassicas throughout the growing season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Mesh and Fabric Weight Affect the Decision</h2>

  <p>
    Both insect netting and row cover come in different weights and densities, which affect how they perform.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Finer mesh netting:</strong> better pest protection, slightly less airflow.</li>
    <li><strong>Lighter row cover:</strong> better airflow, less insulation.</li>
    <li><strong>Heavier row cover:</strong> more insulation, less airflow.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Choosing the right material within each category matters just as much as choosing between them.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overlook</h2>

  <p>
    Both netting and row cover only work well if they are properly secured.
  </p>

  <p>
    Gaps at the edges allow pests to enter and reduce the effectiveness of both systems. Good anchoring often matters more than the specific material.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-clips-and-hoops-for-securing-frost-cloth/">best clips and hoops for securing frost cloth</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Fit by Brassica Situation</h2>

  <div class="scenarioGrid">
    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Early Spring Brassicas</h3>
      <p>
        Row cover is usually the better choice because it adds temperature protection.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Summer Brassicas</h3>
      <p>
        Insect netting works better because it allows more airflow and prevents overheating.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Heavy Pest Pressure</h3>
      <p>
        Fine-mesh insect netting is usually the most reliable option.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="scenarioCard">
      <h3>Best for Variable Conditions</h3>
      <p>
        Using both at different times provides the most flexibility.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Between Them</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Using row cover too long into warm weather:</strong> can overheat plants.</li>
    <li><strong>Using netting too early in cold conditions:</strong> provides little temperature protection.</li>
    <li><strong>Not sealing edges properly:</strong> reduces effectiveness of both.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing mesh or fabric without considering conditions:</strong> leads to mismatched performance.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best results come from matching the material to the season and conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Do</h2>

  <p>
    For most brassica crops, start the season with row cover to protect against cold and early pests, then switch to insect netting as temperatures rise and airflow becomes more important.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose materials based on your typical conditions rather than trying to find one solution for the entire season. In many cases, using both strategically leads to better results than relying on just one.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Row cover protects early. Insect netting protects later. Using both at the right time is often the best approach.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    Insect netting and row cover both protect brassicas, but they serve different roles in the growing season.
  </p>

  <p>
    Row cover is best for early-season protection when cold is still a factor, while insect netting is better for ongoing pest control once temperatures rise. For most gardeners, using both at different stages provides the most effective and flexible protection system.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Match your cover choice to the season, and your brassicas will perform better throughout the year.
  </p>
</section>